Task 3: Coding & Collaboration Platforms

Part A: Coding Practice (HackerRank)

I created an account on HackerRank and started with the “Solve Me First” problem, which simply requires adding two numbers. 
Although the problem itself was very easy, the experience was different from running code on my own system. I had to understand
how HackerRank takes input and produces output in a specific format. At first, this was a bit confusing, but once I understood 
it, things became easier.

After that, I completed the Python Introduction skill test, which covered basic topics like print statements, variables, string
operations, and simple arithmetic. I also received a badge for completing the challenge, which felt motivating. Getting my first
“Accepted” submission was a small but satisfying achievement.

Part B: Google Form (Digital Literacy Quiz)

I created a 5-question quiz using Google Forms to test basic digital literacy among my classmates. The form is connected to 
Google Sheets, so all responses are automatically recorded for easy analysis.

QUIZ LINK - https://forms.gle/ESBB7p3Z3FBmXXJZ6

While designing the quiz, I realized that making good multiple-choice questions is not as simple as it seems. It takes effort 
to create options that are not too obvious. I especially liked creating the short-answer question, as it allows students to 
think more freely instead of choosing fixed options.

Overall, this task was quite useful. I plan to use HackerRank for coding practice, especially for placements, and Google Forms
and Sheets for surveys and group work during my college years.
